        <section id="space">
            <h1>Basics of Space</h2>
                <br>
            ğŸŒŒ What Is Space?

Space begins roughly 100 km (62 miles) above Earth at the KÃ¡rmÃ¡n line. It has:

No breathable air

Extremely low pressure (near vacuum)

Extreme temperatures (very hot in sunlight, very cold in shade)
<br>
<br>

ğŸŒ Major Components of Space
<br>
1. Planets

Bodies that orbit a star and are large enough to be round.

In our Solar System: Mercury, Venus, Earth, Mars, Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus, Neptune

Divided into rocky planets and gas/ice giants
<br>
2. Stars

Massive balls of glowing gas (mostly hydrogen and helium).

Our star is the Sun

Stars produce energy through nuclear fusion
<br>
3. Moons

Natural satellites that orbit planets.

Earth has one; Jupiter and Saturn have dozens
<br>
4. Asteroids & Comets

Asteroids: rocky objects, mostly between Mars and Jupiter

Comets: icy bodies that form glowing tails when near the Sun
<br>
5. Galaxies

Huge systems of stars, gas, dust, and dark matter.

Our galaxy: the Milky Way

There are billions of galaxies in the universe
<br>
<br>
ğŸŒ  The Universe

Everything that exists: space, time, matter, and energy

Estimated age: ~13.8 billion years

Expanding since the Big Bang
<img src="spaceweb1.png" alt="The Universe" width="200px" style="float:right; margin-left:20px; border-radius:10px;">
<br>
<br>
ğŸ›°ï¸ Human Activity in Space

Satellites: communication, GPS, weather

Space stations: International Space Station (ISS)

Exploration: Moon landings, Mars rovers, space telescopes (like Hubble & James Webb)
<br>
<br>

â“Big Questions About Space

<h1>Is there life beyond Earth?</h1> <br>We are not sure if there is life elsewhere in the universe, but scientists are actively searching for signs of microbial life on Mars and the icy moons of Jupiter and Saturn. The discovery of exoplanets in habitable zones around other stars also raises the possibility of extraterrestrial life.
<br>
<br>
<h1>What are dark matter and dark energy?</h1><br>ğŸ•¶ï¸ Dark Matter

What it is:

An invisible form of matter that does not emit, absorb, or reflect light

Makes up about 27% of the universe

How we know it exists:

Galaxies rotate too fast to be held together by visible matter alone

Gravitational effects show there is extra unseen mass

What it does:

Acts like cosmic glue, holding galaxies and galaxy clusters together

What it's made of:

Unknown

Not atoms, not stars, not planets

Possibly exotic particles we haven't detected yet
<br>
<br>
ğŸŒ  Dark Energy

What it is:

A mysterious force causing the expansion of the universe to speed up

Makes up about 68% of the universe

Discovery:

In 1998, scientists found distant galaxies were moving away faster than expected

What it does:

Pushes space itself apart

Opposes gravity on very large scales

What it is exactly:

Completely unknown

Could be a property of space itself (often linked to â€œvacuum energyâ€)
<br>
<br>
âš–ï¸ Dark Matter vs Dark Energy
Feature	Dark Matter	Dark Energy
Visible?	âŒ No	âŒ No
Effect	Pulls things together	Pushes universe apart
Role	Forms galaxies	Accelerates expansion
% of universe	~27%	~68%
<br>
<br>
ğŸ¤¯ The Big Picture

Everything we can see â€” stars, planets, people â€” makes up only about 5% of the universe.

The rest is dark matter and dark energy, meaning:

Most of the universe is made of things we don't yet understand.
<br>
<br>
<img src="spaceweb2.png" alt="A nebula" width="250px" style="float:left; margin-right:20px; border-radius:10px;">
<br>
<br>
<h1>How will the universe end?</h1>

    Cosmologists don't know for sure how the universe will end, but based on current evidence there are a few leading scenarios. Which one happens depends mainly on dark energy and how it behaves over time.
<br>
1. Heat Death (Big Freeze) â€” Most likely

This is the leading model today.

The universe keeps expanding forever.

Galaxies drift apart until new stars can no longer form.

Existing stars burn out; black holes slowly evaporate.

Eventually, the universe becomes cold, dark, and extremely dilute.

End state: Maximum entropy, near absolute zero, no usable energy.
Timescale: Trillions to googols of years.
<br>
<br>
2. Big Rip

If dark energy grows stronger over time:

Expansion accelerates uncontrollably.

Galaxies, stars, planets, and eventually atoms are torn apart.

Spacetime itself is ripped.

End state: Everything is shredded.
Timescale: Possibly tens of billions of years (if this is correct).
<br>
<br>
3. Big Crunch

If gravity eventually overcomes expansion:

Expansion reverses.

The universe collapses back on itself.

Density and temperature rise toward a final singularity.

End state: A hot, dense collapseâ€”possibly a reverse Big Bang.
Status: Currently disfavored by observations.
<br>
<br>
4. Big Bounce

A variation of the Big Crunch:

Collapse triggers a new expansion.

Our universe may be one cycle in an endless sequence.

Status: Speculative, but explored in quantum gravity theories.
<br>
<br>
5. Vacuum Decay

A more exotic possibility:

Our universe may be in a â€œfalse vacuum.â€

A quantum event could trigger a transition to a lower-energy state.

A bubble of new physics expands at near light speed, rewriting reality.

End state: Unknownâ€”laws of physics would change instantly.

What do observations suggest?

Measurements of:

Cosmic expansion

Cosmic microwave background

Dark energy (â‰ˆ70% of the universe)

currently favor eternal expansion, making heat death the most probable outcome.
        </section>

        <section id="cricket">
            <h2>Origins & History</h2>
<h3>Cricket originated in England in the late 16th century.

The first international cricket match was played in 1844 between the USA and Canada.

Test cricket, the oldest format, began in 1877 (England vs Australia).

The Ashes series started in 1882 after Australia beat England at The Oval.

Cricket spread globally through the British Empire.</h3>
<br>
<br>
<h2>Basic Rules & Gameplay</h2>
<h3>
A cricket match is played between two teams of 11 players.

Each team takes turns to bat and bowl.

The batting team scores runs; the bowling team tries to dismiss batters.

A match is played on a circular or oval field with a 22-yard pitch.

There are three wooden stumps topped by two bails at each end.

A batter is out if the bails are dislodged (with some exceptions).</h3>
<br>
<br>
<h2>Ways a Batter Can Be Out</h2>
<h3>
Bowled,

Caught,

Leg Before Wicket (LBW),

Run out,

Stumped,

Hit wicket,

Handled the ball (now merged into â€œobstructing the fieldâ€)and

Timed out (very rare)</h3>
<img src="cricketweb2.png" alt="Batter being bowled" width="300px" style="float:right; margin-left:20px; border-radius:10px;">
<br>
<br>
<h2>Formats of Cricket</h2>
<h3>
Test Cricket: Up to 5 days, unlimited overs.

One Day Internationals (ODIs): 50 overs per side.

T20 Cricket: 20 overs per side, lasts about 3 hours.

The Hundred (England): 100 balls per side.

T10 Cricket: 10 overs per side, very fast-paced.</h3>
<br>
<br>
<h2>Scoring Facts</h2>
<h3>A batter can score 1â€“6 runs per ball (or more via overthrows).

A six is scored when the ball clears the boundary without bouncing.

A four is scored when the ball reaches the boundary after bouncing.

An over consists of 6 legal deliveries.

Extras include no-balls, wides, byes, and leg byes.</h3>

<br>
<br>
<h2>Equipment</h2>
<h3>Cricket bats are traditionally made of English willow.

Balls are made of leather with a cork core.

Cricket balls are usually red (Tests), white (ODIs/T20s), or pink (day-night Tests).

Players wear protective gear like pads, gloves, helmets, and boxes.</h3>
<br>
<br>
<h2>Fielding Facts</h2>
<h3>There are 11 fielders, including the wicketkeeper.

Only two fielders are allowed behind square on the leg side.

Catching the ball cleanly without it touching the ground dismisses the batter.

A fielder can throw the ball to hit the stumps for a run out.</h3>
<br>
<br>
<h2>Bowling Facts</h2>
<h3>Bowlers must keep their arm straight when delivering the ball.

Fast bowlers can exceed 150 km/h (93 mph).

Spin bowlers use wrist or finger rotation to deceive batters.

Types of bowling include fast, swing, seam, off-spin, leg-spin.</h3>
<br>
<br>
<h2>Famous Players</h2>
<h3>Sir Don Bradman (Australia) had a Test batting average of 99.94.

Sachin Tendulkar is the highest run-scorer in international cricket.

Muttiah Muralitharan has the most Test wickets (800).

Jacques Kallis is one of the greatest all-rounders.

MS Dhoni is one of the most successful captains.
Virat Kohli is my favorite player!</h3>
<img src="cricketweb1.png" border-radius="10px" alt="Virat Kohli batting" width="300px" style="float:right; margin-left:20px;">
<br>
<br>
<h2>Records & Milestones</h2>
<h3>Highest individual Test score: 400* (Brian Lara).

Fastest century in ODIs: 31 balls (AB de Villiers).

First double century in ODIs: Sachin Tendulkar.

Most sixes in international cricket: Chris Gayle.

Longest Test match lasted 12 days (1939, timeless Test).</h3>
<br>
<br>
<h2>World Cups & Major Tournaments</h2>
<h3>The ICC Cricket World Cup began in 1975.

Australia has won the most Cricket World Cups.

The T20 World Cup began in 2007.

The Indian Premier League (IPL) is the richest cricket league.

The Big Bash League (BBL) is Australia's T20 league.</h3>
<br>
<br>
<h2>Countries Where Cricket Is Popular</h2>
<h3>India, Pakistan, Sri Lanka, Bangladesh

England, Australia, New Zealand

South Africa, West Indies

Afghanistan, Ireland</h3>
<br>
<br>
<h2>Strategy & Tactics</h2>
<h3>Captains decide the batting order and field placements.

Pitch conditions affect how much the ball spins or swings.

Weather and light can impact play.

Reverse swing occurs when one side of the ball is rougher than the other.</h3>
<br>
<br>
<h2>Fun & Unusual Facts</h2>
<h3>A batter can be not out even after scoring 0 (a â€œduckâ€).

There are different types of ducks: golden duck, diamond duck.

Matches can end in a tie, draw, or no result.

A hat-trick is three wickets in three consecutive balls.

Umpires can give batters out using DRS (Decision Review System).

Cricket is the second most popular sport in the world by fan base.</h3>
        </section>

        <section id="roblox">
            <h2>ğŸ§± Basic Roblox Facts</h2>

Roblox launched publicly in 2006.

It was created by David Baszucki and Erik Cassel.

Roblox is not just a gameâ€”it's a game creation platform.

Most Roblox games are called â€œexperiences.â€

Roblox is available on PC, Mac, iOS, Android, Xbox, and some VR devices.

Roblox uses its own game engine, Roblox Studio.
<br>
<br>
<h2>ğŸ‘¥ Community & Players</h2>

Roblox has hundreds of millions of monthly active users worldwide.

A large portion of its players are under 18, but many adults also play and create.

Players are called â€œRobloxians.â€

Roblox supports over 20 languages.

Some Roblox developers started as kids and later became professional game designers.

Roblox hosts virtual concerts, events, and brand experiences.
<br>
<img src="robloxweb2.png" border-radius="10px" alt="Roblox community" width="300px" style="float:right; margin-left:20px;">
<br>
<br>
<h2>ğŸ’» Development & Coding</h2>

Roblox games are scripted using Lua (specifically a version called Luau).

Roblox Studio is free to download and use.

Developers can work solo or in teams on the same game.

Roblox supports physics simulation, including gravity, collisions, and joints.

You can publish a game to Roblox with one click from Studio.

Some Roblox games have been worked on for 10+ years.
<br>
<br>
<h2>ğŸ’° Robux & Economy</h2>

Roblox's virtual currency is called Robux.

Developers earn Robux through game passes, developer products, and paid access.

Robux can be exchanged for real money through the Developer Exchange (DevEx).

Roblox pays out hundreds of millions of dollars per year to developers.

Some developers have become millionaires from Roblox games.

Limited items can be resold (UGC Limiteds).
<br>
<br>
<h2>ğŸ¨ Avatars & Customization</h2>

Roblox avatars were originally blocky and yellow by default.

You can customize avatars with layered clothing.

There are thousands of free avatar items.

Users can create and sell UGC (User-Generated Content) items.

Roblox introduced dynamic faces with facial animation.

R15 avatars have 15 body parts; R6 avatars have 6.
<br>
<br>
<h2>ğŸ•¹ï¸ Games & Genres</h2>

Popular genres include roleplay, simulator, obby, FPS, tycoon, horror, and story games.

Some Roblox games have billions of visits.

â€œObbyâ€ is short for obstacle course.

Roblox FPS games often use custom-built gun systems, not defaults.

Many trends in Roblox games spread virally across the platform.
<br>
<br>
<h2>ğŸµ Audio, Music & Events</h2>

Roblox once allowed any audio uploads, which caused copyright issues.

Roblox has hosted concerts by artists like Lil Nas X, Twenty One Pilots, and Elton John.

Sound effects and music are handled through asset IDs.

Voice chat exists and is age-verified.

Roblox supports spatial voice chat.
<br>
<br>
<h2>ğŸ›¡ï¸ Safety & Moderation</h2>

Roblox uses AI and human moderators.

Chat filtering is stricter for younger users.

Parents can set account restrictions and PINs.

Accounts can be terminated or banned for rule violations.

Roblox has a report system for players and content.
<br>
<br>
<h2>ğŸ§  Fun & Weird Facts</h2>

The â€œOofâ€ death sound was removed due to a licensing issue.

Early Roblox was called Dynablocks.

Roblox physics used to be extremely glitchy and chaotic.

Some Roblox myths (like John Doe) were entirely fan-made.

There are Roblox museums built inside Roblox.

Some Roblox items are worth thousands of real dollars.

Roblox has been used for education and coding classes.

Roblox is sometimes described as a metaverse.
<br>
<img src="robloxweb1.png" border-radius="20px" alt="Roblox logo" width="200px" style="float:right; margin-left:20px;">
<br>
<br>
<h2>ğŸ“ˆ Business & Company Facts</h2>

Roblox Corporation is a publicly traded company (NYSE: RBLX).

Roblox earns money mainly from Robux sales.

The company headquarters is in California, USA.

Roblox spends heavily on infrastructure and moderation.

Developers receive a share of platform revenue
        </section>

        <section id="minecraft">
            <h2>ğŸŸ© Basic Minecraft Facts</h2>

Minecraft was officially released in 2011.

It was created by Markus â€œNotchâ€ Persson.

Minecraft was later bought by Microsoft in 2014.

It is the best-selling video game of all time.

Minecraft is available on PC, console, mobile, and VR.

The game has no official endingâ€”you choose how to play.

Minecraft has survival, creative, hardcore, and spectator modes.
<br><br>
<h2>ğŸŒ World & Gameplay Facts</h2>

Minecraft worlds are procedurally generated.

A Minecraft world is practically infinite.

The Overworld, Nether, and End are separate dimensions.

The Ender Dragon is considered the game's final boss, but the game continues after beating it.

Villagers have professions and schedules.

Creepers were created by accident from a pig model mistake.

Spiders can climb walls but only if there's something to cling to.

Endermen can pick up certain blocks.

Minecraft has over 1,000 different items and blocks.

Redstone works like digital logic, similar to real-life circuits.
<br>
<img src="Minecraftweb2.png" alt="Minecraft world" width="300px" style="float:right; margin-left:20px; border-radius:10px;">
<br><br>
<h2>ğŸ”§ Technical & Hidden Facts</h2>

Java Edition and Bedrock Edition have different mechanics.

Quasi-connectivity exists only in Java Edition.

Slime chunks are fixed per world seed.

Falling sand and gravel are entities, not blocks.

You can build working calculators and computers using redstone.

The game runs at 20 ticks per second.

Some mobs spawn only at specific light levels.

Minecraft speedrunners use Ender Pearl and Blaze Rod RNG manipulation.
<br><br>
<h2>ğŸ§Ÿ Mobs & Creatures</h2>

There are hostile, neutral, and passive mobs.

The Warden is blind and detects vibrations.

The Wither is the only mob created by players.

Ghasts' cries were made from a sleeping cat sound.

Axolotls were added to raise awareness for endangered species.

The Chicken Jockey is one of the rarest mob combinations.

Baby zombies are faster than adult zombies.
<br><br>
<h2>ğŸµ Music & Sounds</h2>

Minecraft's original music was composed by C418.

Some music tracks only play in specific biomes.

Music discs can only be obtained in special ways (like creepers killed by skeletons).

Minecraft's music is intentionally quiet and atmospheric.

The End music changes as you progress.
<br><br>
<h2>ğŸ§  Lore & Easter Eggs</h2>

The End Poem appears after defeating the Ender Dragon.

Dinnerbone or Grumm makes mobs upside-down.

Naming a sheep â€œjeb_â€ makes it rainbow-colored.

The game hints at ancient civilizations through structures.

Disc 11 and Disc 13 are considered creepy lore items.

Strongholds appear broken, suggesting something went wrong.
